00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:07.630
The Soldier Who Voluntarily Became a Prisoner
in Auschwitz

00:00:07.630 --> 00:00:22.840
Nazi troops invaded Poland on September 1,
1939, despite the best efforts of Captain

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:27.960
Witold Pilecki and his fellow Polish soldiers.
On November 9th of that same year, Witold

00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:34.300
and Major Wlodarkiewicz founded the Tajna
Armia Polska (TAP or Polish Secret Army),

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:38.460
an underground organization that eventually
became consolidated with other resistance

00:00:38.460 --> 00:00:40.140
forces into The Home Army.

00:00:40.140 --> 00:00:44.440
Not long after the formation of organized
widespread Polish Resistance, its members

00:00:44.440 --> 00:00:49.070
began hearing reports of the conditions within
the newly constructed Auschwitz Concentration

00:00:49.070 --> 00:00:54.390
Camp put into operation in the Spring of 1940.
Those first reports originated with prisoners

00:00:54.390 --> 00:00:59.210
released from the camp and from civilians
such as railroad employees and local residents.

00:00:59.210 --> 00:01:03.200
In order to cut through the very troubling
rumors and figure out exactly what was going

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:09.240
on there, Pilecki came up with a bold plan-
become a prisoner at Auschwitz. With a little

00:01:09.240 --> 00:01:11.700
convincing, his superiors eventually agreed
to allow him to go.

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:14.979
In order to help protect his wife and children
after he was captured, he took on the alias

00:01:14.979 --> 00:01:19.330
Tomasz Serafinski, much to the chagrin of
the real Tomasz Serafinski who was thought

00:01:19.330 --> 00:01:24.320
to be dead at the time (hence why his papers
and identity were chosen), but was not. Later,

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:28.960
the real Tomasz had some trouble because of
Pilecki using his papers and name (more on

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:29.960
this in the Bonus Facts below).

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:34.159
According to Eleonora Ostrowska, owner of
an apartment Pilecki was at when he was taken,

00:01:34.159 --> 00:01:38.630
when a Nazi roundup began (lapanka, where
a city block would suddenly be closed off

00:01:38.630 --> 00:01:42.549
and most of the civilians inside would be
rounded up and sent to slave labor camps and

00:01:42.549 --> 00:01:47.240
sometimes even just mass-executed on the spot),
a member of the resistance came to help Pilecki

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:52.190
hide. Instead, Ostrowska said “Witold rejected
those opportunities and didn’t even try

00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:57.079
to hide in my flat.” She reported that soon,
a German soldier knocked at the door and Pilecki

00:01:57.079 --> 00:02:01.100
whispered to her “Report that I have fulfilled
the order,” and then opened the door and

00:02:01.100 --> 00:02:06.110
was taken by the soldier along with about
2,000 other Poles in Warsaw on September 19,

00:02:06.110 --> 00:02:07.110
1940.

00:02:07.110 --> 00:02:11.380
It is important to note here that he didn’t
really know if he’d be sent to Auschwitz

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:16.639
at this point. As Dr. Daniel Paliwoda noted
of Pilecki’s capture, “Since the AB Aktion

00:02:16.639 --> 00:02:19.930
and roundups were still going on, the Nazis
could have tortured and executed him in

00:02:19.930 --> 00:02:24.790
occupied Warsaw’s Pawiak, Mokotów, or any
other Gestapo-run prison. They could have

00:02:24.790 --> 00:02:27.879
taken him to Palmiry to murder him in the
forest. At the very least, they could have

00:02:27.879 --> 00:02:30.819
sent him to a forced labor colony somewhere
in Germany.”

00:02:30.819 --> 00:02:34.939
While he was willingly surrendering with the
hope of being sent to Auschwitz, Pilecki lamented

00:02:34.939 --> 00:02:38.599
the behavior of his fellow countrymen during
the roundup. “What really annoyed me the

00:02:38.599 --> 00:02:43.569
most was the passivity of this group of Poles.
All those picked up were already showing signs

00:02:43.569 --> 00:02:47.909
of crowd psychology, the result being that
our whole crowd behaved like a herd of passive

00:02:47.909 --> 00:02:52.930
sheep. A simple thought kept nagging me: stir
up everyone and get this mass of people moving.”

00:02:52.930 --> 00:02:57.480
As he had hoped (perhaps the only person to
ever hope such a thing), he was sent to Auschwitz.

00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:00.189
He later described his experience upon arrival:
